Cite content {1: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy for medical and dental applications: a comprehensive review'. Abstract: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy is one of the most significant analytical techniques that has been developed in the past few decades. A broad range of biological and nonbiological applications ranging from an individual cell to organs and tissues has been investigated through NMR. Various aspects of this technique are still under research, and many functions of the NMR are still pending a better understanding and acknowledgment. Therefore, this review is aimed at providing a general overview of the main principles, types of this technique, and the advantages and disadvantages of NMR spectroscopy. In addition, an insight into the current uses of NMR in the field of medicine and dentistry and ongoing developments of NMR spectroscopy for future applications has been discussed.'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy for medical and dental applications: a comprehensive review' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 2: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 3: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 4: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Principles of nuclear magnetic resonance microscopy'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Principles of nuclear magnetic resonance microscopy' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 5: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 6: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Advances in low-field nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) technologies applied for characterization of pore space inside rocks: a critical review'. Abstract: 'Low-field nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) has become a widely used technique for characterizing pore space in rocks. This paper provides a critical review of advances in low-field NMR technologies applied to pore space characterization. The review covers the principles of NMR relaxation and diffusion, experimental methods, and data analysis techniques. Applications include porosity, pore size distribution, permeability, and fluid typing. The paper also discusses the challenges and limitations of low-field NMR, such as the effects of internal gradients and paramagnetic minerals. Future developments in hardware and software are outlined.'", "The paper titled 'Advances in low-field nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) technologies applied for characterization of pore space inside rocks: a critical review' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 7: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 8: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 9: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 10: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 11: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance T1–T2 spectra in heavy oil reservoirs'. Abstract: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) T1-T2 spectra are used to characterize heavy oil reservoirs. The T1-T2 maps provide information on fluid types and pore sizes. In heavy oil reservoirs, the NMR response is complicated by the high viscosity and complex composition of the oil. This study presents T1-T2 measurements on core samples from heavy oil reservoirs. The results show that heavy oil has distinct T1-T2 signatures that can be used to distinguish it from water and light oil. The T1/T2 ratio is correlated with oil viscosity. The study demonstrates the potential of T1-T2 maps for evaluating heavy oil reservoirs.'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic resonance T1–T2 spectra in heavy oil reservoirs' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 12: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Characterization of fluid distributions in porous media by NMR techniques'. Abstract: 'NMR techniques are used to characterize fluid distributions in porous media. The study combines NMR relaxation and diffusion measurements to probe the spatial distribution of fluids. Experiments were performed on model porous media and rock cores with different fluid saturations. The results show that the NMR response is sensitive to the fluid distribution, with different relaxation and diffusion characteristics for different saturation states. The data are analyzed using theoretical models to infer the fluid distribution at the pore scale. The study demonstrates the potential of NMR for non-invasive characterization of multiphase fluid distributions.'", "The paper titled 'Characterization of fluid distributions in porous media by NMR techniques' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 13: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 14: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 15: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 16: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 17: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 18: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 19: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic relaxation in porous media'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic relaxation in porous media' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 20: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Pulsed nuclear magnetic resonance studies of porosity, movable fluid, and permeability of sandstones'. Abstract: 'Pulsed nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is used to study porosity, movable fluid, and permeability of sandstones. The NMR measurements provide relaxation time distributions that are correlated with pore size and fluid saturation. The movable fluid fraction is estimated from the NMR signal. Permeability is estimated from the relaxation times using empirical correlations. The study establishes the basis for using NMR in petrophysical evaluation of sandstones.'", "The paper titled 'Pulsed nuclear magnetic resonance studies of porosity, movable fluid, and permeability of sandstones' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 21: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Proton magnetic resonance and pore size variations in reservoir sandstones'. Abstract: 'Proton magnetic resonance (NMR) is used to study pore size variations in reservoir sandstones. NMR T2 relaxation time measurements were performed on a suite of sandstone samples with different pore sizes. The results show that the T2 distribution reflects the pore size distribution, with larger pores having longer T2 times. The relationship between T2 and pore size is affected by surface relaxivity, which varies with mineralogy. The study provides insights into the interpretation of NMR logs in terms of pore size and reservoir quality.'", "The paper titled 'Proton magnetic resonance and pore size variations in reservoir sandstones' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 22: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 23: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Relaxation effects in nuclear magnetic resonance absorption'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Relaxation effects in nuclear magnetic resonance absorption' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 24: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 25: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 26: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Effect of internal magnetic-field gradients on nuclear-magnetic-resonance measurements and nuclear-magnetic-resonance-based pore-network characterization'. Abstract: 'The effect of internal magnetic-field gradients on NMR measurements and pore-network characterization is investigated. Internal gradients arise from susceptibility differences between the solid matrix and pore fluids. They affect relaxation times and diffusion measurements. The study uses numerical simulations and experiments on rock cores to quantify the effects. The results show that internal gradients can lead to errors in pore size estimation and permeability prediction. A method for correcting NMR data for internal gradients is proposed. The study improves the accuracy of NMR-based pore-network characterization.'", "The paper titled 'Effect of internal magnetic-field gradients on nuclear-magnetic-resonance measurements and nuclear-magnetic-resonance-based pore-network characterization' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 27: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Effect of mineral composition on transverse relaxation time distributions and MR imaging of tight rocks from offshore Ireland'. Abstract: 'Tight reservoir rocks are characterized by low porosity and permeability, which complicates fluid flow and production. Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is a widely used technique to assess pore space and fluid properties in such rocks. However, the interpretation of NMR data in tight rocks is challenging due to the complex pore structure and the presence of different minerals. In this study, we investigate the effect of mineral composition on transverse relaxation time (T2) distributions and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of tight rocks from offshore Ireland. We conducted NMR measurements on a suite of rock samples with varying mineralogy, including quartz, clay, and carbonate. The results show that the T2 distributions are significantly affected by the presence of paramagnetic minerals such as clays and iron-bearing carbonates, which enhance relaxation rates. MRI images reveal heterogeneous fluid distributions influenced by mineralogy and pore structure. This study provides insights into the interpretation of NMR data in tight rocks and highlights the importance of considering mineral composition when assessing reservoir quality.'", "The paper titled 'Effect of mineral composition on transverse relaxation time distributions and MR imaging of tight rocks from offshore Ireland' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 28: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Simulation and experimental measurements of internal magnetic field gradients and NMR transverse relaxation times (T2) in sandstone rocks'. Abstract: 'Internal magnetic field gradients in porous media arise from susceptibility differences between the solid matrix and the pore fluid. These gradients affect NMR transverse relaxation times (T2) and can complicate the interpretation of NMR data. This study combines numerical simulations and experimental measurements to investigate internal gradients in sandstone rocks. The simulations use realistic pore geometries from micro-CT images. The results show that internal gradients are highly heterogeneous and depend on the pore structure and the magnetic susceptibility of the minerals. The simulations are validated by comparison with experimental T2 measurements at different magnetic field strengths. The study provides insights into the effect of internal gradients on NMR relaxation in sandstones.'", "The paper titled 'Simulation and experimental measurements of internal magnetic field gradients and NMR transverse relaxation times (T2) in sandstone rocks' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 29: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 30: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Confinement effects on dipolar relaxation by translational dynamics of liquids in porous silica glasses'. Abstract: 'The effect of confinement on the nuclear magnetic relaxation of liquids in porous silica glasses is investigated theoretically and experimentally. A model is developed that accounts for the translational dynamics of liquid molecules near the pore surface and their effect on dipolar relaxation. The model predicts that the relaxation rate is enhanced in confined geometries due to the reduced dimensionality of molecular motion. Experimental measurements on liquids in porous silica glasses with different pore sizes confirm the model predictions. The study provides insights into the molecular dynamics of confined liquids and the interpretation of NMR relaxation data in porous media.'", "The paper titled 'Confinement effects on dipolar relaxation by translational dynamics of liquids in porous silica glasses' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 31: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 32: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 33: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Determination of oil and water compositions of oil/water emulsions using low field NMR relaxometry'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Determination of oil and water compositions of oil/water emulsions using low field NMR relaxometry' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 34: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Relaxation mechanisms and shales'. Abstract: 'The relaxation mechanisms in shales are reviewed. Shales have complex compositions, including organic matter, clay minerals, and paramagnetic minerals, which affect NMR relaxation. The review covers the contributions of different relaxation mechanisms, including surface relaxation, bulk relaxation, and diffusion in internal gradients. The effects of pore size, fluid type, and saturation are discussed. The review provides a framework for interpreting NMR data in shales and identifying the key factors controlling relaxation.'", "The paper titled 'Relaxation mechanisms and shales' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 35: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Wettability, saturation, and viscosity from NMR measurements'. Abstract: 'This paper presents a method for estimating wettability, fluid saturations, and viscosity from nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) measurements in reservoir rocks. The method is based on analysis of NMR relaxation time distributions and diffusion measurements. Wettability is inferred from the relaxation times of oil and water, which are affected by surface interactions. Saturations are determined from the amplitudes of the NMR signals. Viscosity is estimated from the relaxation times of oil, which depend on molecular dynamics. The method was tested on core samples with different wettability and fluid properties. The results show good agreement with independent measurements.'", "The paper titled 'Wettability, saturation, and viscosity from NMR measurements' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 36: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 37: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 38: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance surface relaxivity and its advanced application in calculating pore size distributions'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic resonance surface relaxivity and its advanced application in calculating pore size distributions' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 39: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 40: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Quantification of microporosity by nuclear magnetic resonance relaxation of water imbibed in porous media'. Abstract: 'Microporosity in porous media affects fluid storage and transport. This study presents a method for quantifying microporosity using nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) relaxation of water imbibed in the pores. The method is based on the fact that water in micropores has shorter relaxation times than water in macropores due to surface relaxation. NMR T2 relaxation time measurements were performed on porous media with different microporosities. The results show that the amplitude of the short T2 component is proportional to the microporosity. The method is applied to soil and rock samples and validated with independent measurements.'", "The paper titled 'Quantification of microporosity by nuclear magnetic resonance relaxation of water imbibed in porous media' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 41: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 42: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Low-field nuclear magnetic resonance characterization of carbonate and sandstone reservoirs from rock spring uplift of wyoming'. Abstract: 'Low-field NMR is used to characterize carbonate and sandstone reservoirs from the Rock Spring Uplift of Wyoming. NMR T2 relaxation time measurements provide information on pore size distributions and fluid saturations. The results are compared with conventional core analysis. The study shows that NMR can distinguish between different pore types and fluid populations. The NMR data are used to estimate permeability and to evaluate reservoir quality. The study demonstrates the value of low-field NMR for reservoir characterization.'", "The paper titled 'Low-field nuclear magnetic resonance characterization of carbonate and sandstone reservoirs from rock spring uplift of wyoming' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 43: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Effect of paramagnetic species on T 1, T 2 and T 1 /T 2 NMR relaxation times of liquids in porous CuSO 4 /Al 2 O 3'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Effect of paramagnetic species on T 1, T 2 and T 1 /T 2 NMR relaxation times of liquids in porous CuSO 4 /Al 2 O 3' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 44: ("There is a paper. Title: 'A laboratory study to determine the effect of iron oxides on proton NMR measurements'. Abstract: 'Iron oxides in rocks and sediments affect proton NMR measurements by enhancing surface relaxation. This laboratory study investigates the effect of iron oxides on NMR T2 relaxation times. Synthetic samples with controlled iron oxide content and distribution were prepared. NMR measurements show that iron oxides reduce T2 relaxation times and can mask the pore size information. The effect depends on the iron oxide concentration and its proximity to the pore surface. The study provides insights into the interpretation of NMR data in iron-rich formations.'", "The paper titled 'A laboratory study to determine the effect of iron oxides on proton NMR measurements' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 45: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Effect of paramagnetic ions on NMR relaxation of fluids at solid surfaces'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Effect of paramagnetic ions on NMR relaxation of fluids at solid surfaces' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 46: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 47: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Capillary trapping quantification in sandstones using NMR relaxometry'. Abstract: 'Capillary trapping is an important mechanism for geological storage of CO2. This study uses nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) relaxometry to quantify capillary trapping in sandstones. NMR T2 relaxation time measurements were performed on sandstone cores during drainage and imbibition cycles with supercritical CO2 and brine. The results show that the amount of trapped CO2 can be quantified from the NMR signal. The trapped saturation depends on the initial CO2 saturation and the pore structure. The NMR method provides a non-destructive way to measure capillary trapping in porous media.'", "The paper titled 'Capillary trapping quantification in sandstones using NMR relaxometry' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 48: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Spin diffusion measurements: spin echoes in the presence of a time-dependent field gradient'. Abstract: 'A method for measuring spin diffusion using spin echoes in the presence of a time-dependent field gradient is presented. The method uses a pulsed field gradient to encode spatial information and measure the diffusion coefficient. The theory of the experiment is developed, and experimental results on water and glycerol are presented. The pulsed field gradient method is widely used for diffusion measurements in NMR and MRI.'", "The paper titled 'Spin diffusion measurements: spin echoes in the presence of a time-dependent field gradient' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 49: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance relaxation and diffusion in the presence of internal gradients: the effect of magnetic field strength'. Abstract: 'Internal magnetic field gradients in porous media affect NMR relaxation and diffusion measurements. This study investigates the effect of magnetic field strength on internal gradients and their impact on NMR data. Experiments were performed on rock cores at different field strengths. The results show that internal gradients increase with field strength, leading to enhanced relaxation and diffusion attenuation. The effect is more pronounced in rocks with high susceptibility contrast. The study provides guidelines for selecting the appropriate field strength and pulse sequences to mitigate the effects of internal gradients.'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic resonance relaxation and diffusion in the presence of internal gradients: the effect of magnetic field strength' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 50: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 51: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 52: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 53: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Spin echoes'. Abstract: 'The spin echo phenomenon is described theoretically and experimentally. A sequence of two radiofrequency pulses produces an echo signal at a time equal to the pulse spacing. The echo amplitude is affected by diffusion in an inhomogeneous magnetic field. The spin echo method provides a way to measure relaxation times and diffusion coefficients. This paper is a classic in the field of NMR.'", "The paper titled 'Spin echoes' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 54: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 55: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 56: ("There is a paper. Title: 'A three-part study of NMR longitudinal relaxation properties of water-saturated sandstones'. Abstract: 'This three-part study investigates the NMR longitudinal relaxation (T1) properties of water-saturated sandstones. Part 1 presents experimental T1 measurements on a variety of sandstones. Part 2 develops a model relating T1 to pore size distribution and surface relaxivity. Part 3 discusses the implications for permeability estimation from NMR. The study shows that T1 is sensitive to pore size and that the T1 distribution can be used to estimate permeability. The results provide a foundation for NMR logging applications.'", "The paper titled 'A three-part study of NMR longitudinal relaxation properties of water-saturated sandstones' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 57: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 58: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Modified spin-echo method for measuring nuclear relaxation times'. Abstract: 'A modified spin-echo method for measuring nuclear relaxation times is presented. The method uses a sequence of 90° and 180° pulses to refocus the magnetization and eliminate the effects of diffusion and field inhomogeneity. The echo amplitude decays with the transverse relaxation time T2. The method is applied to liquids and solids and provides accurate T2 measurements. The modified spin-echo method is